window.MODULES=window.MODULES||{};window.MODULES["acute-coronary-syndromes"]={"slug": "acute-coronary-syndromes", "title": "Acute Chest Pain and Acute Coronary Syndromes", "tagline": "A fellowship-depth framework for chest pain triage, the Fourth Universal Definition of MI, high-sensitivity troponin interpretation, ECG STEMI-equivalents, and guideline-directed antithrombotic and invasive management aligned to the 2025 ACC/AHA ACS guideline.", "level": 3, "readMin": 44, "sections": [{"id": "learning-objectives", "title": "Learning Objectives", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "This module builds from resident-level triage to first-year-fellow command of the acute coronary syndrome (ACS) spectrum. By the end you should reason fluently from an undifferentiated chest pain presentation to a mechanism-anchored diagnosis and a guideline-directed disposition, using the 2025 ACC/AHA unified ACS guideline and the 2023 ESC ACS guideline as your reference frameworks."}, {"type": "list", "items": ["Apply the Fourth Universal Definition of Myocardial Infarction and classify all five MI types by mechanism.", "Distinguish acute MI from acute non-ischemic myocardial injury and chronic myocardial injury using the rise/fall and ischemia framework.", "Interpret high-sensitivity cardiac troponin: the 99th-percentile upper reference limit, sex-specific cutoffs, delta (serial-change) logic, and the 0/1h and 0/2h algorithms.", "Recognize the ECG STEMI-equivalents that mandate emergent reperfusion despite absent classic ST-elevation, and separate them from patterns of global subendocardial ischemia.", "Map coronary territories to ECG leads and anticipate the mechanical complications of transmural infarction.", "Select antithrombotic therapy and time the invasive strategy according to NSTE-ACS risk category, and prescribe contemporary secondary prevention."]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 2, "text": "The single most common cognitive error on a cardiology consult service is conflating <strong>myocardial injury</strong> (a troponin finding) with <strong>myocardial infarction</strong> (a clinical diagnosis requiring ischemia). Internalize that separation before anything else in this module."}]}, {"id": "why-it-matters", "title": "Why It Matters", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Chest pain accounts for one of the highest-volume presentations to emergency departments, yet the majority of these patients do not have ACS. The clinical task is asymmetric: missing an ACS carries catastrophic consequences, while over-testing generates false positives, downstream angiography, and iatrogenic harm. Fellowship-level performance means neither under- nor over-calling."}, {"type": "p", "text": "The stakes are mechanistic. In ST-elevation MI, myocardium dies at a rate that makes time-to-reperfusion the dominant determinant of infarct size and mortality. In NSTE-ACS, the culprit is typically a non-occlusive thrombus on a disrupted plaque, and the therapeutic window is measured in hours rather than minutes, shifting the emphasis to antithrombotic therapy and risk-stratified angiography."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 1, "text": "A normal initial troponin does not exclude ACS. Early presenters (within 1-2 hours of symptom onset) can have a negative first sample; serial sampling and the delta change are what confer diagnostic safety."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "The paradigm is shifting from the anatomic STEMI/NSTEMI dichotomy toward an <strong>Occlusion MI (OMI) versus Non-Occlusion MI (NOMI)</strong> framework. A meaningful fraction of acutely occluded coronaries do not meet STEMI voltage criteria yet benefit from emergent reperfusion, which is precisely why STEMI-equivalents matter so much. This remains a conceptual lens, not yet a guideline-endorsed replacement for the ST-elevation threshold."}]}, {"id": "essential-physiology", "title": "Essential Physiology: Plaque, Thrombus, and Supply-Demand", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "The unifying substrate of Type 1 ACS is coronary atherothrombosis: an atherosclerotic plaque becomes unstable and a thrombus forms on its surface. The two dominant mechanisms are plaque rupture (a thin fibrous cap tears, exposing the lipid-rich necrotic core and tissue factor to flowing blood) and plaque erosion (endothelial denudation over a more fibrous, less lipid-laden plaque, more common in younger women and smokers). A minority arise from a calcified nodule."}, {"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "Exposed tissue factor triggers the coagulation cascade while shear and collagen activate platelets. The resulting platelet-fibrin thrombus determines the syndrome: a fully occlusive, persistent thrombus produces transmural ischemia and ST-elevation; a subtotally occlusive or intermittently occlusive thrombus, often with distal embolization, produces NSTE-ACS."}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 2, "entries": [{"term": "Vulnerable plaque", "def": "A lesion prone to disruption, classically the thin-cap fibroatheroma: a large lipid-rich necrotic core, a thin fibrous cap (on the order of <65-85 microns), macrophage infiltration, and positive (outward) remodeling. Such lesions are frequently angiographically non-obstructive before they cause an event."}, {"term": "Plaque rupture", "def": "Structural failure of the fibrous cap exposing thrombogenic core contents. The dominant mechanism of Type 1 MI, especially in men and in lipid-rich plaque."}, {"term": "Plaque erosion", "def": "Thrombus over an intact but endothelially denuded plaque, without cap rupture. Increasingly recognized; may be amenable to a less aggressive (non-stenting) strategy in selected cases under intravascular imaging guidance."}, {"term": "Coronary vasospasm", "def": "Focal or diffuse smooth-muscle hypercontractility (Prinzmetal/variant angina) causing transient transmural ischemia with reversible ST-elevation, classically at rest and overnight; a non-atherothrombotic cause of the ACS presentation."}]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "MINOCA (Myocardial Infarction with Non-Obstructive Coronary Arteries, <50% stenosis) is a working diagnosis, not a final one. The fellow's job is to find the mechanism: plaque disruption seen on intravascular imaging (OCT/IVUS), epicardial or microvascular spasm (provocation testing), coronary embolism, or spontaneous coronary artery dissection (SCAD). CMR frequently reclassifies these, distinguishing true MI from myocarditis or takotsubo, which are causes of injury that mimic MINOCA."}, {"type": "p", "depth": 2, "text": "Type 2 MI has an entirely different physiology: a mismatch between myocardial oxygen supply and demand in the absence of an acute atherothrombotic event. Tachyarrhythmia, hypotension, severe anemia, hypoxemia, hypertensive emergency, and coronary spasm or embolism can all tip a heart, with or without underlying fixed obstruction, into ischemia. Recognizing that the treatment is correction of the precipitant, not routine dual antiplatelet therapy and heparin, is a defining fellow-level distinction."}]}, {"id": "definitions-and-classification", "title": "The Fourth Universal Definition of MI", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "The Fourth Universal Definition of Myocardial Infarction (2018) is the reference framework. Its central move is to separate injury from infarction and then to classify infarction by mechanism."}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 1, "entries": [{"term": "Myocardial injury", "def": "Detection of a cardiac troponin value above the 99th-percentile upper reference limit (URL). Injury is acute if there is a rise and/or fall of values, and chronic if the values are persistently elevated and stable."}, {"term": "Myocardial infarction (MI)", "def": "Acute myocardial injury (rise and/or fall of cTn with at least one value above the 99th-percentile URL) PLUS clinical evidence of acute myocardial ischemia. Ischemia must be documented by at least one of: ischemic symptoms; new ischemic ECG changes; development of pathological Q waves; imaging evidence of new loss of viable myocardium or new regional wall-motion abnormality in an ischemic pattern; or identification of a coronary thrombus by angiography or autopsy."}]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 1, "text": "The load-bearing word is <strong>ischemia</strong>. Troponin above the URL with a rise/fall establishes acute injury. Only when you add objective ischemia does injury become infarction. This one sentence resolves most bedside confusion."}, {"type": "table", "depth": 2, "caption": "The five types of myocardial infarction (Fourth Universal Definition)", "head": ["Type", "Mechanism", "Key features / management anchor"], "rows": [["Type 1", "Atherothrombotic — plaque rupture or erosion with intracoronary thrombus", "The classic ACS. Antithrombotic therapy plus reperfusion/revascularization."], ["Type 2", "Oxygen supply-demand mismatch WITHOUT acute atherothrombosis", "Tachyarrhythmia, hypotension/shock, anemia, hypoxemia, hypertensive emergency, spasm, embolism. Treat the precipitant; revascularize only if fixed obstructive disease is contributory."], ["Type 3", "Cardiac death with symptoms/ECG suggestive of ischemia BEFORE biomarkers could be drawn or before they rose", "Sudden cardiac death attributable to MI without biomarker confirmation (e.g., death before sampling)."], ["Type 4a", "PCI-related MI (<=48h of the procedure)", "cTn >5x the 99th-percentile URL (in patients with normal baseline) PLUS new ischemic ECG/imaging/angiographic evidence."], ["Type 4b", "Stent thrombosis", "MI associated with documented stent thrombosis on angiography or autopsy. Timed as acute, subacute, late, or very late."], ["Type 4c", "In-stent restenosis", "MI associated with restenosis (>=50%) at a previously stented segment, without another culprit lesion."], ["Type 5", "CABG-related MI (<=48h of surgery)", "cTn >10x the 99th-percentile URL (normal baseline) PLUS new pathological Q waves/LBBB, new graft or native occlusion, or imaging evidence of new viable-myocardium loss."]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "Note the procedural biomarker thresholds are deliberately high and asymmetric: >5x URL for PCI (Type 4a) and >10x URL for CABG (Type 5), because both procedures cause some baseline troponin release. A modest post-procedural bump is expected injury; only a large rise plus ancillary evidence qualifies as procedural MI. Do not label every post-CABG troponin an infarction."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 2, "text": "Type 4b (stent thrombosis) is a time-critical emergency that classically presents as STEMI. In any patient with recent PCI presenting with ST-elevation, assume stent thrombosis and activate the cath lab; ask specifically about antiplatelet adherence and recent interruption of DAPT."}]}, {"id": "injury-vs-infarction", "title": "MI vs Acute Injury vs Chronic Injury", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "This is the interpretive engine of the entire troponin era. Given any elevated troponin, ask two orthogonal questions: (1) Is the value dynamic (a rise and/or fall on serial testing) or stable? (2) Is there objective ischemia? The answers place the patient in one of three boxes."}, {"type": "table", "depth": 1, "caption": "The diagnostic triad from a troponin above the 99th-percentile URL", "head": ["Pattern", "Troponin kinetics", "Ischemia present?", "Diagnosis"], "rows": [["MI", "Rise and/or fall", "Yes", "Myocardial infarction (then subtype by mechanism)"], ["Acute non-ischemic injury", "Rise and/or fall", "No", "Acute myocardial injury, non-ischemic"], ["Chronic injury", "Stable / no significant change", "No (by definition)", "Chronic myocardial injury"]]}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 2, "entries": [{"term": "Acute non-ischemic myocardial injury — causes", "def": "Myocarditis, takotsubo (stress) cardiomyopathy, acute heart failure decompensation, tachyarrhythmia, sepsis/critical illness, acute pulmonary embolism with RV strain, cardiac contusion or procedures (ablation, cardioversion, defibrillator shocks), and cardiotoxic chemotherapy. There is a dynamic rise/fall, but the mechanism is not myocardial ischemia."}, {"term": "Chronic myocardial injury — causes", "def": "Structural heart disease with persistent low-grade release: chronic kidney disease (reduced clearance and true myocardial stress), stable structural heart disease (LVH, HFpEF/HFrEF), infiltrative cardiomyopathy (amyloid), and pulmonary hypertension. Values are elevated but stable across serial draws."}]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 1, "text": "A stable elevated troponin in a patient with CKD and no ischemic story is usually chronic injury, not ACS. The serial delta is what tells you, which is exactly why you draw more than one sample."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "The rise/fall requirement cuts both ways. A patient can present late, at the peak of their troponin curve, where two closely spaced samples look nearly flat and mimic chronic injury. Anchor the interpretation to the clinical pretest probability and the whole trajectory, and repeat sampling if the story is convincing. Kinetics inform, they do not overrule, a compelling ischemic presentation."}]}, {"id": "troponin-biology", "title": "Troponin Biology and High-Sensitivity Assays", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Cardiac troponins I and T are structural regulatory proteins of the myocyte contractile apparatus. Because they are cardiac-specific isoforms, their appearance in blood is a sensitive and specific marker of myocardial injury of any cause. The assay generation determines how early and how precisely we can detect that injury."}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 1, "entries": [{"term": "99th-percentile URL", "def": "The diagnostic threshold: the concentration exceeded by only 1% of a normal reference population. A value above the URL defines myocardial injury. The URL is assay-specific — there is no universal numeric cutoff transferable between platforms."}, {"term": "High-sensitivity cardiac troponin (hs-cTn)", "def": "An assay that can measure troponin in a substantial proportion (>50%) of a normal reference population and has a coefficient of variation <=10% at the 99th percentile. This precision at low concentrations is what enables early rule-out and short (1-2h) serial intervals."}, {"term": "Delta (serial change)", "def": "The absolute change in troponin between serial samples. hs-cTn algorithms are built on absolute deltas (in ng/L), which discriminate acute injury from chronic elevation better than relative/percentage change, particularly at higher baseline values."}]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 2, "text": "hs-cTn assays report in <strong>ng/L</strong> (whole numbers); older conventional assays report in ng/mL or ug/L. A tenfold reporting-unit confusion at the bedside is a real and dangerous error — always confirm the unit and the assay's own 99th-percentile URL before interpreting a number."}, {"type": "table", "depth": 2, "caption": "Sex-specific 99th-percentile URLs (illustrative; always use your assay's package insert)", "head": ["Assay", "Overall URL", "Female URL", "Male URL"], "rows": [["hs-cTnT (representative)", "~14 ng/L", "~9 ng/L", "~15 ng/L"], ["hs-cTnI (representative)", "assay-specific", "lower", "higher"]]}, {"type": "p", "depth": 2, "text": "Sex-specific cutoffs matter because women have lower baseline troponin concentrations and lower left-ventricular mass. Using a single overall URL under-diagnoses MI in women, contributing to documented sex disparities in ACS recognition. Where the lab reports sex-specific thresholds, use them."}, {"type": "list", "depth": 2, "label": "Non-ACS causes of an elevated troponin (a differential, not a false positive)", "items": ["Structural/hemodynamic cardiac: heart failure, tachy- and brady-arrhythmia, hypertensive emergency, aortic stenosis, hypertrophic cardiomyopathy", "Non-ischemic myocardial: myocarditis, takotsubo, infiltrative disease, cardiac contusion, ablation/cardioversion/ICD shocks", "Pulmonary: acute pulmonary embolism (RV strain), pulmonary hypertension, severe respiratory failure", "Systemic/critical illness: sepsis and septic shock, severe anemia, extreme exertion (endurance events)", "Renal: chronic kidney disease (reduced clearance and true chronic injury)", "Neurologic: acute stroke, subarachnoid hemorrhage (neurogenic myocardial stunning)"]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 1, "text": "\"Elevated troponin\" is never a diagnosis. It is a finding demanding a mechanism. Reflexively treating every elevated troponin as ACS — anticoagulating a patient whose real problem is sepsis, PE, or GI bleeding with demand ischemia — causes harm."}]}, {"id": "rule-out-algorithms", "title": "The 0/1h and 0/2h hs-cTn Algorithms", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "The ESC and the 2025 ACC/AHA ACS guideline endorse accelerated diagnostic protocols that use a baseline hs-cTn plus a single repeat at 1 or 2 hours, interpreted against assay-specific absolute thresholds, to rule out or rule in MI rapidly in patients without ST-elevation. These algorithms are validated for the specific assay whose cutoffs they cite; the numbers are not interchangeable across platforms."}, {"type": "steps", "depth": 1, "label": "0/1h hs-cTn algorithm (conceptual structure)", "items": ["Rule-out: a very low baseline value (below the assay's limit of detection) in a patient presenting >3h after symptom onset, OR a low baseline value with a small 1h delta below the assay-specific threshold.", "Rule-in: a markedly elevated baseline value, OR a significant absolute 1h delta above the assay-specific rule-in threshold, indicating acute injury.", "Observe: patients who meet neither rule-out nor rule-in criteria enter an observation zone requiring a further sample (e.g., at 3h) and clinical reassessment."]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 1, "text": "These algorithms are diagnostic accelerators, not clinical overrides. A patient with ongoing ischemic pain, hemodynamic instability, or a dynamic ECG bypasses the pathway and goes to the appropriate urgent management regardless of the troponin trajectory."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "The rule-out arm leans on the assay's <strong>limit of detection</strong> and on time-from-onset because very early presenters may not yet have crossed the threshold — the \"troponin-blind\" interval. This is why a single undetectable value at presentation is only safe when combined with either an adequate time-from-onset or a confirmatory second sample. The 0/2h protocol trades an hour of throughput for slightly wider, more forgiving deltas; institutions choose one and standardize it."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 2, "text": "Do not apply one assay's numeric cutoffs to another assay's result, and do not apply an accelerated protocol to a patient in whom it was never validated (very early presenter without a confirmatory later sample, or a renal patient in whom baseline elevation degrades specificity). Know which assay your institution runs and its exact thresholds."}]}, {"id": "acs-spectrum", "title": "UA, NSTEMI, and STEMI: The ACS Spectrum", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "ACS is a clinical spectrum defined at the bedside by the ECG and by biomarkers. The first fork is the presenting ECG: ST-elevation (or equivalent) versus no ST-elevation. Within the non-ST-elevation group, the troponin then separates unstable angina from NSTEMI."}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 1, "entries": [{"term": "Unstable angina (UA)", "def": "Ischemic symptoms at rest, of new onset, or in an accelerating (crescendo) pattern, WITHOUT a rise in troponin above the URL. In the hs-cTn era UA has become uncommon, because more of these patients are reclassified as NSTEMI once a sensitive assay detects minor injury."}, {"term": "NSTEMI", "def": "Ischemic symptoms with a dynamic troponin rise/fall above the URL but WITHOUT persistent ST-elevation. The ECG may show ST-depression, T-wave inversion, or be normal. Typically a non-occlusive or intermittently occlusive thrombus."}, {"term": "STEMI", "def": "Acute ischemia with persistent ST-elevation meeting criteria (or a STEMI-equivalent), reflecting acute total or near-total coronary occlusion. A reperfusion emergency."}]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 2, "text": "The clean UA/NSTEMI/STEMI taxonomy has a blind spot: some acutely occluded arteries (posterior, left circumflex, de Winter pattern) do not produce criteria-positive ST-elevation and get mislabeled NSTEMI, delaying reperfusion. This is the practical argument behind the emerging Occlusion-MI framework and the reason STEMI-equivalents are a core fellow competency."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 1, "text": "UA is a retrospective, troponin-negative diagnosis; you cannot confirm it until serial hs-cTn stays below the URL. Until then, an ischemic-sounding rest pain is managed as possible NSTEMI."}]}, {"id": "stemi-criteria-equivalents", "title": "STEMI Criteria and STEMI-Equivalents", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Classic STEMI criteria require new ST-elevation at the J-point in at least two contiguous leads: >=1 mm in most leads; in leads V2-V3, >=2 mm in men >=40 years, >=2.5 mm in men <40, and >=1.5 mm in women. New (or presumably new) left bundle branch block is no longer, by itself, a STEMI criterion — it requires additional evidence of occlusion (e.g., Sgarbossa)."}, {"type": "figure", "depth": 1, "src": "../assets/fig/stemi-12lead.jpg", "alt": "12-lead ECG showing anterior ST-segment elevation myocardial infarction", "caption": "Anterior STEMI: ST-segment elevation across the precordial leads (V2–V4) with hyperacute T waves — an anterior-wall injury current from proximal LAD occlusion.", "credit": "CC BY 4.0, via Wikimedia Commons", "source": "https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:ST_elevation_myocardial_infarction_ECG_(cropped).jpg"}, {"type": "table", "depth": 1, "caption": "STEMI-equivalents and high-risk ECG patterns without classic ST-elevation", "head": ["Pattern", "ECG signature", "Culprit / significance"], "rows": [["de Winter T-waves", "Upsloping ST-depression at the J-point in precordial leads with tall, symmetric T-waves; often no overt ST-elevation", "Proximal LAD occlusion. A true occlusion equivalent — activate the cath lab."], ["Wellens syndrome", "Biphasic (Type A) or deep symmetric (Type B) T-wave inversions in V2-V3, typically PAIN-FREE with preserved R-waves", "Critical proximal LAD stenosis. High risk of imminent extensive anterior MI; do NOT stress test — angiography."], ["Posterior MI", "ST-depression V1-V3 with tall R-waves and upright T-waves; confirm with posterior leads V7-V9 showing ST-elevation", "Left circumflex (or RCA) occlusion. A true STEMI hiding as anterior ST-depression."], ["aVR ST-elevation with diffuse ST-depression", "ST-elevation in aVR (and often V1) with ST-depression in >=6 leads", "Pattern of global subendocardial ischemia (left main, proximal LAD, or severe triple-vessel disease), NOT a single acute occlusion. Warrants urgent angiography, usually after stabilization and medical therapy, rather than reflexive emergent cath-lab activation unless ischemia is refractory or the patient is unstable."], ["LBBB / paced rhythm (Sgarbossa)", "Concordant ST-elevation >=1 mm; concordant ST-depression >=1 mm V1-V3; or excessively discordant ST-elevation (Smith-modified: ST/S ratio <=-0.25)", "Diagnoses acute MI in the presence of LBBB or a ventricular-paced rhythm."], ["Hyperacute T-waves", "Broad, tall, symmetric T-waves early in occlusion, before ST-elevation matures", "Earliest sign of occlusion; repeat the ECG in minutes — it evolves."]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 1, "text": "Wellens is a warning, not a reassurance. The pain-free interval with deep T-wave inversions signals a critically stenosed LAD at risk of re-occluding into a massive anterior infarct. These patients go to angiography, not to a treadmill."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "Do not overcall aVR. ST-elevation in aVR with diffuse ST-depression is most often <strong>subendocardial supply-demand ischemia</strong> — it can be driven by tachycardia, anemia, hypotension, or severe stenotic disease, and it is not on its own an OMI. Treat the precipitant and ischemia medically, risk-stratify, and pursue urgent (not blind emergent) angiography; reserve immediate cath-lab activation for refractory ischemia, instability, or an accompanying true occlusion pattern. Contrast this with de Winter and posterior MI, which are single-vessel occlusions that do mandate emergent reperfusion."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "The Smith-modified Sgarbossa criterion replaces the original absolute 5 mm discordance rule with a proportional ST/S ratio of <=-0.25, substantially improving sensitivity for occlusion in LBBB and paced rhythms. Combined with serial ECGs and posterior/right-sided leads, this is the toolkit that catches the occlusions a STEMI-voltage-only reading misses."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 1, "text": "Isolated ST-depression maximal in V1-V3 is posterior STEMI until proven otherwise. Reach for posterior leads (V7-V9) — a single millimeter of ST-elevation there confirms an occlusion that mandates reperfusion."}]}, {"id": "coronary-territories", "title": "Coronary Territories and ECG Localization", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Localizing the culprit from the ECG anticipates complications and informs the angiographic plan. Contiguous lead groups map to arterial territories."}, {"type": "table", "depth": 1, "caption": "ECG lead groups, territory, and likely culprit", "head": ["Leads", "Territory", "Usual culprit"], "rows": [["V1-V2", "Septal", "LAD (septal branches)"], ["V3-V4", "Anterior", "LAD"], ["V1-V6, I, aVL", "Extensive anterior", "Proximal LAD / left main"], ["I, aVL, V5-V6", "Lateral", "LAD (diagonal) or LCx"], ["II, III, aVF", "Inferior", "RCA (~80-85%) or LCx (~15-20%)"], ["V7-V9 (ST-elev); V1-V3 (recip. ST-dep)", "Posterior", "LCx or RCA"], ["V3R-V4R (ST-elev)", "Right ventricle", "Proximal RCA"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 1, "text": "In inferior STEMI, always obtain right-sided leads. RV infarction (proximal RCA) makes the patient preload-dependent: nitrates and other preload reducers can precipitate profound hypotension. These patients need fluids, not nitroglycerin."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 2, "text": "In inferior STEMI, lead III ST-elevation exceeding lead II, with ST-depression in I and aVL, points to an RCA culprit; a more lateral/precordial reciprocal pattern points to LCx. ST-depression in aVL is an early and sensitive reciprocal marker of inferior injury — sometimes the first thing to appear."}]}, {"id": "clinical-presentation", "title": "Clinical Presentation and History", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "The history remains the highest-yield initial tool. Classic ischemic pain is substernal pressure or tightness, exertional or at rest, radiating to the arm(s) or jaw, with diaphoresis, dyspnea, or nausea. But the features that most raise or lower probability are the ones a fellow weights deliberately."}, {"type": "list", "depth": 1, "label": "Features that raise probability of ACS", "items": ["Pain radiating to both arms or the right arm/shoulder", "Exertional pain reproducing a prior anginal pattern, or a clear crescendo pattern", "Diaphoresis and vomiting accompanying the pain", "Pain similar to a prior confirmed MI"]}, {"type": "list", "depth": 1, "label": "Features that lower probability (but never exclude)", "items": ["Pleuritic, positional, or reproducible-on-palpation pain", "Sharp/stabbing quality in a low-risk patient", "Very brief (seconds) or constant for days without change"]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 1, "text": "Atypical and silent presentations dominate in older adults, women, and patients with diabetes: dyspnea, fatigue, syncope, epigastric discomfort, or delirium may be the only manifestation. A low threshold for an ECG and troponin in these groups is a safety imperative."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 2, "text": "In the chest pain patient, keep the immediately life-threatening non-ACS diagnoses live at all times: aortic dissection (tearing pain, pulse/blood-pressure differential, mediastinal widening — anticoagulation is harmful here), pulmonary embolism, tension pneumothorax, esophageal rupture, and pericarditis with tamponade. The first act after ACS enters the differential is a 12-lead ECG within 10 minutes — but the dissection question must be answered before you anticoagulate."}]}, {"id": "diagnostic-approach", "title": "Diagnostic Approach and Risk Stratification", "body": [{"type": "steps", "depth": 1, "label": "Initial approach to acute chest pain", "items": ["Obtain a 12-lead ECG within 10 minutes of first medical contact; repeat serially (every 15-30 min) if the first is non-diagnostic and symptoms persist.", "Draw hs-cTn at presentation and time the repeat per your institution's validated 0/1h or 0/2h protocol.", "Apply a structured risk pathway (e.g., HEART score) to integrate history, ECG, age/risk factors, and troponin.", "Triage: ST-elevation or equivalent triggers immediate reperfusion; NSTE-ACS is risk-stratified for invasive timing; low-risk chest pain is considered for early discharge with follow-up."]}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 2, "entries": [{"term": "HEART score", "def": "History, ECG, Age, Risk factors, and initial Troponin, each scored 0-2. A low score (0-3) identifies patients at low short-term risk of major adverse cardiac events who are candidates for accelerated discharge; higher scores warrant admission and further evaluation. Widely validated for ED chest pain triage."}, {"term": "GRACE score", "def": "A validated risk model (age, heart rate, systolic BP, creatinine, Killip class, cardiac arrest at admission, ST deviation, biomarker elevation) estimating in-hospital and post-discharge mortality in ACS. A GRACE score above a defined threshold (commonly >140) marks high risk and supports an early invasive strategy in NSTE-ACS."}, {"term": "TIMI risk score", "def": "A 7-item score for NSTE-ACS predicting death, MI, and urgent revascularization; simpler than GRACE but less discriminating. Useful for rapid bedside gestalt."}]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "Risk scores augment, they do not replace, clinical judgment, and they are only as good as the population they were derived in. The HEART pathway pairs the score with serial troponin; a low HEART score with a rising delta is not low risk. Use the score to structure disposition, not to override a dynamic biomarker or an evolving ECG."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 1, "text": "Coronary CT angiography is a powerful rule-out in low-to-intermediate risk patients with a normal or non-diagnostic ECG and negative troponin: its high negative predictive value can safely exclude obstructive disease and expedite discharge. It is less useful in higher-risk patients, in whom invasive angiography is more direct."}]}, {"id": "guideline-directed-management", "title": "Guideline-Directed Management", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Management follows the ECG fork. STEMI is a reperfusion emergency; NSTE-ACS is risk-stratified for invasive timing. Antithrombotic therapy — antiplatelet plus anticoagulant — is common to both, layered on anti-ischemic and secondary-prevention therapy. The 2025 ACC/AHA unified ACS guideline is the current US reference and supersedes the 2013 STEMI and 2014 NSTE-ACS documents."}, {"type": "steps", "depth": 1, "label": "STEMI reperfusion", "items": ["Primary PCI is the preferred strategy when it can be delivered promptly: a first-medical-contact-to-device time of <=90 minutes at a PCI-capable center, or <=120 minutes when transfer is required.", "If timely PCI is not achievable, give fibrinolysis (in the absence of contraindications) within 30 minutes of arrival (door-to-needle), then transfer for angiography (pharmaco-invasive strategy).", "Use radial access preferentially, give dual antiplatelet therapy and an anticoagulant per protocol, and do not delay activation for laboratory results."]}, {"type": "table", "depth": 2, "caption": "Antithrombotic agents in ACS", "head": ["Class / agent", "Role", "Fellow-level notes"], "rows": [["Aspirin", "Immediate, all ACS", "Loading dose chewed for rapid absorption; lifelong maintenance."], ["Ticagrelor / prasugrel", "P2Y12 inhibitor, preferred in most ACS", "More potent/consistent than clopidogrel. Prasugrel is contraindicated with prior stroke/TIA and generally avoided at >=75y or <60 kg; ticagrelor requires twice-daily dosing and causes dyspnea."], ["Clopidogrel", "P2Y12 inhibitor", "Used when potent agents are contraindicated, with fibrinolysis, or when high bleeding risk/anticoagulation coexists. Variable metabolism (CYP2C19)."], ["Unfractionated heparin", "Anticoagulant, periprocedural", "Titratable, reversible, preferred when early PCI is planned."], ["Enoxaparin / fondaparinux", "Anticoagulant", "Fondaparinux favored in conservatively managed NSTE-ACS for lower bleeding; needs adjunctive UFH at PCI to avoid catheter thrombosis."], ["GP IIb/IIIa inhibitors", "Potent antiplatelet, bailout", "Reserved for large thrombus burden or periprocedural complications, not routine upstream use."], ["Cangrelor", "IV P2Y12 inhibitor", "Rapid on/off; useful when oral loading is not feasible (e.g., intubated, vomiting)."]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "DAPT strategy is increasingly individualized. Default is 12 months of DAPT after ACS, but the 2025 guideline supports de-escalation options to reduce bleeding in selected patients: shortening DAPT to 1-3 months followed by P2Y12-inhibitor monotherapy (usually ticagrelor), or switching from a potent agent to clopidogrel. High ischemic risk favors longer/more potent therapy; high bleeding risk favors abbreviation. Match the strategy to the individual, not a fixed 12-month reflex."}, {"type": "table", "depth": 2, "caption": "NSTE-ACS risk category and timing of invasive strategy", "head": ["Risk category", "Triggers", "Invasive timing"], "rows": [["Very high", "Hemodynamic instability/cardiogenic shock, refractory/recurrent ischemia, life-threatening arrhythmia, mechanical complication, acute heart failure attributable to ACS", "Immediate (<2h)"], ["High", "Rise/fall of troponin consistent with MI, dynamic ST/T changes, GRACE score high (e.g., >140)", "Early invasive (<24h)"], ["Intermediate", "Diabetes, renal insufficiency, LVEF <40%, prior PCI/CABG, intermediate GRACE, post-infarct angina", "Invasive (during admission)"], ["Low", "No recurrent symptoms and none of the above", "Selective invasive after non-invasive testing (ischemia/CTA)"]]}, {"type": "list", "depth": 1, "label": "Adjunctive and secondary-prevention therapy", "items": ["High-intensity statin started early in all ACS regardless of baseline LDL, with early addition of ezetimibe and, when the LDL-C target (<55 mg/dL and >=50% reduction) is not met, a PCSK9-directed agent", "Early oral beta-blocker within 24h if no contraindication (avoid in acute heart failure, hypotension, high AV-block risk, low-output state, or cocaine-associated ACS)", "ACE inhibitor/ARB especially with reduced LVEF, heart failure, hypertension, or diabetes", "Mineralocorticoid receptor antagonist for post-MI LVEF <=40% with heart failure or diabetes", "Nitrates and analgesia for symptom relief (nitrates contraindicated in RV infarction and recent phosphodiesterase-5 inhibitor use; minimize opioids, which blunt oral antiplatelet absorption)", "Cardiac rehabilitation referral and aggressive risk-factor modification at discharge"]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "The long-term beta-blocker paradigm has narrowed. REDUCE-AMI and subsequent trials found no reduction in death or recurrent MI from routine long-term beta-blockade after MI in patients with <strong>preserved LVEF</strong> and no other indication. Beta-blockers remain firmly indicated for reduced LVEF (HFrEF), significant arrhythmia, or ongoing angina; for the uncomplicated preserved-EF patient, the 2025 guideline reflects this equipoise and long-term routine use is no longer a strong mandate."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 2, "text": "Type 2 MI is NOT managed with reflexive dual antiplatelet therapy and anticoagulation. The intervention is correcting the supply-demand precipitant (rate control, transfusion for critical anemia, oxygenation, blood-pressure control). Anticoagulating a bleeding or septic patient because the troponin rose causes direct harm."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "Routine P2Y12 pretreatment before knowing coronary anatomy in NSTE-ACS is not recommended when early angiography is planned, because it complicates a patient who may need urgent CABG. For STEMI going to primary PCI, upstream loading is standard. Know which pathway your patient is on before you load."}]}, {"id": "mechanical-complications", "title": "Mechanical Complications of MI", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Transmural infarction, particularly when reperfusion is late or absent, can produce catastrophic mechanical failure days after the index event. These are the complications a fellow must recognize instantly because they are rapidly fatal and surgically or percutaneously treatable."}, {"type": "table", "depth": 2, "caption": "Mechanical complications of acute MI", "head": ["Complication", "Typical timing / setting", "Presentation & clue"], "rows": [["Papillary muscle rupture", "2-7 days; inferior MI (posteromedial papillary muscle, single RCA/PDA blood supply)", "Acute severe mitral regurgitation, flash pulmonary edema, new murmur (may be soft); emergent surgery."], ["Ventricular septal rupture", "3-5 days; anterior or inferior MI", "New harsh holosystolic murmur, biventricular failure, left-to-right shunt (O2 step-up on right-heart catheterization); high mortality."], ["Free-wall rupture", "3-7 days; large transmural anterior MI, first infarct, older patients", "Sudden pulseless electrical activity from tamponade; frequently fatal before intervention."], ["Pseudoaneurysm", "Subacute; contained rupture", "Contained by pericardium/thrombus; high rupture risk — surgical repair."], ["True LV aneurysm", "Weeks-months; anterior MI", "Persistent ST-elevation, heart failure, thrombus/embolism risk, ventricular arrhythmia."], ["Post-MI pericarditis / Dressler", "Early (peri-infarct) or weeks later (immune-mediated Dressler)", "Pleuritic pain, friction rub, diffuse ST-elevation; treat with high-dose aspirin (avoid non-aspirin NSAIDs and steroids acutely post-MI)."]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 1, "text": "A new murmur with hemodynamic collapse days after an MI is a mechanical complication until proven otherwise. Get an urgent echocardiogram and call cardiac surgery — do not attribute the deterioration to recurrent ischemia alone."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "Distinguishing acute severe MR from VSD at the bedside: both cause a new systolic murmur and cardiogenic shock, but the VSD produces an oxygen step-up from RA to RV on right-heart catheterization, while acute MR produces giant V-waves on the PCWP tracing. Mechanical circulatory support (IABP, Impella, or VA-ECMO) can bridge either to definitive surgery."}]}, {"id": "advanced-fellow-concepts", "title": "Advanced Fellow Concepts", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 2, "text": "Beyond the core algorithm lie the syndromes that separate a competent resident from a fellow: the MINOCA workup, the specific populations, and the evidence base that governs revascularization decisions."}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 3, "entries": [{"term": "SCAD (spontaneous coronary artery dissection)", "def": "A non-atherosclerotic cause of ACS, predominantly in younger women, peripartum, and those with fibromuscular dysplasia or connective-tissue disorders. Management is conservative in most cases because the intramural hematoma often heals spontaneously and PCI carries a high complication rate; intravascular imaging and expert operators guide the minority who need intervention."}, {"term": "Complete vs culprit-only revascularization", "def": "In STEMI with multivessel disease and no shock, trial evidence (COMPLETE) supports complete revascularization of significant non-culprit lesions (staged or during the index admission) over culprit-only PCI to reduce recurrent events; the 2025 ACC/AHA guideline recommends complete revascularization in multivessel STEMI and NSTEMI. In cardiogenic shock, CULPRIT-SHOCK favors culprit-lesion-only PCI at the index procedure rather than routine immediate multivessel intervention."}, {"term": "Invasive vs conservative in stable ischemia", "def": "ISCHEMIA showed that in stable coronary disease with moderate-to-severe ischemia and no left-main disease, an initial invasive strategy did not reduce hard cardiovascular events versus optimal medical therapy — a framework that does NOT apply to ACS, where the acute thrombotic substrate changes the calculus entirely."}]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "In cardiogenic shock complicating MI, the evidence base is nuanced: emergent revascularization of the culprit is life-saving, but routine immediate complete revascularization increased harm (CULPRIT-SHOCK), and a routine survival benefit of intra-aortic balloon counterpulsation was not demonstrated in randomized trials (IABP-SHOCK II). Microaxial flow-pump support (DanGer Shock) showed a survival benefit in selected STEMI-related shock patients at the cost of higher complication rates — patient selection is everything."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 2, "text": "Cocaine-associated chest pain reframes the pharmacology: benzodiazepines and nitrates are first-line, and beta-blockers are traditionally avoided because of the concern for unopposed alpha-mediated coronary vasoconstriction. The mechanism is spasm and demand, layered on accelerated atherosclerosis."}]}, {"id": "bedside-pearls", "title": "Bedside Pearls", "body": [{"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 1, "text": "Repeat the ECG. A single non-diagnostic tracing in an ongoing-pain patient is a snapshot of an evolving process — serial ECGs catch the hyperacute T-wave that becomes ST-elevation twenty minutes later."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 1, "text": "The delta beats the number. A troponin of 40 ng/L that was 38 ng/L six hours ago is chronic injury; a troponin of 40 that was 8 is acute injury. Always interpret the trajectory, not the isolated value."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 2, "text": "In inferior STEMI, look immediately at aVL for reciprocal ST-depression and at right-sided leads for RV involvement. Those two glances change your fluid and nitrate decisions within the first minute."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 1, "text": "Pain relief from a GI cocktail or nitroglycerin does not rule in or rule out ACS. Response to therapy is not a diagnostic test — commit to the objective data."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "When the troponin is up but the story is not ischemic, name the alternative mechanism explicitly in your note (PE, sepsis, myocarditis, CKD-chronic). Documenting the differential forces the discipline that prevents both missed MI and inappropriate anticoagulation."}]}, {"id": "common-mistakes", "title": "Common Mistakes", "body": [{"type": "list", "depth": 1, "items": ["Calling every elevated troponin an MI — ignoring that infarction requires ischemia, not just injury.", "Anchoring on a single troponin value instead of the serial delta, especially in CKD where baseline elevation is expected.", "Missing STEMI-equivalents — reading a posterior MI as anterior ischemia, or dismissing de Winter T-waves as non-specific.", "Reflexively activating the cath lab for aVR elevation with diffuse ST-depression when the real problem is treatable subendocardial supply-demand ischemia.", "Giving nitrates in RV infarction and precipitating hypotension.", "Managing Type 2 MI as if it were Type 1 — anticoagulating a supply-demand mismatch instead of correcting the precipitant.", "Failing to consider aortic dissection before anticoagulating a chest-pain patient.", "Sending a Wellens-pattern patient to a stress test instead of angiography.", "Applying one hs-cTn assay's cutoffs or accelerated protocol to a different assay's result."]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 1, "text": "The two highest-consequence errors sit at opposite poles: discharging an occlusion mislabeled NSTEMI, and anticoagulating a demand-ischemia or dissection patient. Both are prevented by the same discipline — anchor every decision to mechanism, serial data, and the whole ECG."}]}, {"id": "references", "title": "References", "body": [{"type": "list", "items": ["Fourth Universal Definition of Myocardial Infarction (2018) — ESC/ACC/AHA/WHF Consensus Document (Thygesen et al.).", "2025 ACC/AHA/ACEP/NAEMSP/SCAI Guideline for the Management of Patients With Acute Coronary Syndromes (unified US ACS guideline).", "2023 ESC Guidelines for the Management of Acute Coronary Syndromes (unified ACS guideline).", "2021 ACC/AHA/SCAI Guideline for Coronary Artery Revascularization.", "Superseded but historically foundational: 2013 ACCF/AHA STEMI Guideline and 2014 AHA/ACC NSTE-ACS Guideline.", "Landmark trials: ISCHEMIA (invasive vs conservative in stable disease), COMPLETE (complete revascularization in STEMI), CULPRIT-SHOCK (culprit-only PCI in shock), DanGer Shock (microaxial pump in STEMI shock), REDUCE-AMI (beta-blockade after MI with preserved EF)."]}]}], "quiz": [{"stem": "A 68-year-old man with sepsis and a hemoglobin of 6.2 g/dL develops a troponin rise from 12 to 95 ng/L with new ST-depressions during a run of atrial fibrillation with rapid ventricular response. Coronary angiography later shows non-obstructive disease. Which MI type and management approach is correct?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Type 1 MI; load dual antiplatelet therapy and heparinize"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Type 2 MI; treat the precipitants — rate control, transfusion, source control"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Chronic myocardial injury; no further action"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Type 4b MI; activate the cath lab for stent thrombosis"}], "correct": "B", "explanation": "There is a dynamic rise/fall with ischemic ECG changes (so this is MI, not mere injury), but the mechanism is supply-demand mismatch from tachyarrhythmia and severe anemia in sepsis with non-obstructive coronaries — Type 2 MI. Management targets the precipitants; reflexive DAPT and anticoagulation would risk harm without addressing the cause."}, {"stem": "A patient presents pain-free after an episode of chest pain. The ECG shows deep symmetric T-wave inversions in V2-V3 with preserved R-waves and normal troponin. What is the appropriate next step?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Discharge home given the pain-free state and negative troponin"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Exercise treadmill stress test to provoke ischemia"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Coronary angiography for a Wellens pattern"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Reassure and repeat troponin in 6 hours only"}], "correct": "C", "explanation": "This is Wellens syndrome — a pattern of critical proximal LAD stenosis. The pain-free interval and normal troponin are falsely reassuring; these patients are at high risk of imminent extensive anterior infarction. Stress testing is dangerous and can precipitate MI. The correct action is angiography."}, {"stem": "Which finding best distinguishes acute myocardial infarction from acute non-ischemic myocardial injury?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "A troponin value above the 99th-percentile URL"}, {"key": "B", "text": "A rise and/or fall in troponin on serial testing"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Objective evidence of myocardial ischemia accompanying the troponin rise/fall"}, {"key": "D", "text": "An absolute troponin value greater than 5 times the URL"}], "correct": "C", "explanation": "Both MI and acute non-ischemic injury show a rise/fall above the URL (options A and B are shared by both). The differentiator per the Fourth Universal Definition is objective ischemia — symptoms, new ischemic ECG changes, imaging evidence, or angiographic thrombus. Injury plus ischemia equals infarction; injury without ischemia is non-ischemic injury."}, {"stem": "A patient with inferior STEMI (ST-elevation in II, III, aVF) becomes profoundly hypotensive after a dose of sublingual nitroglycerin. What is the most likely explanation?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Anaphylaxis to nitroglycerin"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Right ventricular infarction with preload dependence"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Ventricular septal rupture"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Papillary muscle rupture with acute mitral regurgitation"}], "correct": "B", "explanation": "Inferior STEMI from a proximal RCA occlusion frequently involves the right ventricle, making the patient preload-dependent. Nitrates reduce preload and can precipitate profound hypotension. Right-sided leads (V3R-V4R) should be obtained in every inferior STEMI, and these patients are managed with fluids rather than preload reducers."}, {"stem": "A hemodynamically stable patient has ST-elevation in aVR and V1 with 2 mm of ST-depression across the inferolateral leads during ongoing chest pain and a heart rate of 140. Which statement best reflects contemporary interpretation and management?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "This is a STEMI-equivalent from a single acute occlusion; activate the cath lab for immediate emergent PCI"}, {"key": "B", "text": "This pattern reflects global subendocardial ischemia (left main or multivessel/supply-demand); treat ischemia and precipitants and pursue urgent angiography, reserving emergent activation for refractory ischemia or instability"}, {"key": "C", "text": "aVR elevation is an artifact and can be ignored if troponin is negative"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Give fibrinolytics immediately since PCI is not indicated for this pattern"}], "correct": "B", "explanation": "ST-elevation in aVR with diffuse ST-depression signals global subendocardial ischemia — left main, severe multivessel disease, or a supply-demand insult (here, marked tachycardia) — rather than a single-vessel occlusion. Modern guidance does not treat it as a straightforward OMI mandating blind emergent PCI. Correct the precipitant, treat ischemia medically, and arrange urgent angiography, escalating to emergent activation only for refractory ischemia or hemodynamic instability. Fibrinolytics are not appropriate for this non-occlusion pattern."}], "takeaways": ["Myocardial infarction requires a rise and/or fall of troponin with at least one value above the 99th-percentile URL AND objective evidence of ischemia; troponin elevation alone defines myocardial injury, not infarction.", "The core diagnostic bifurcation is ischemic versus non-ischemic and dynamic versus stable: rise/fall + ischemia = MI; rise/fall without ischemia = acute non-ischemic injury; stable elevation = chronic injury.", "Type 1 MI is atherothrombotic plaque disruption; Type 2 MI is oxygen supply-demand mismatch without acute plaque event — the management diverges fundamentally and Type 2 is frequently missed or mislabeled.", "High-sensitivity troponin enables validated 0/1h and 0/2h algorithms using absolute delta changes and sex-specific 99th-percentile cutoffs; the magnitude and trajectory of change, not a single value, drive rule-in and rule-out.", "True STEMI-equivalents (de Winter T-waves, Wellens, posterior MI, Sgarbossa-positive LBBB) mandate emergent reperfusion despite absent classic ST-elevation, whereas aVR elevation with diffuse ST-depression signals left-main/multivessel subendocardial ischemia and warrants urgent — not reflexive emergent — angiography; this ECG discrimination is the highest-yield fellow competency.", "NSTE-ACS risk stratification (very-high, high, intermediate, low) determines invasive timing — immediate (<2h), early (<24h), or selective — and antithrombotic strategy follows the same risk architecture, per the 2025 ACC/AHA and 2023 ESC ACS guidelines."], "references": ["Fourth Universal Definition of Myocardial Infarction (2018) — ESC/ACC/AHA/WHF Consensus Document (Thygesen et al.)", "2025 ACC/AHA/ACEP/NAEMSP/SCAI Guideline for the Management of Patients With Acute Coronary Syndromes (unified US ACS guideline)", "2023 ESC Guidelines for the Management of Acute Coronary Syndromes (unified ACS guideline)", "2021 ACC/AHA/SCAI Guideline for Coronary Artery Revascularization", "Historically foundational (superseded by the 2025 unified guideline): 2013 ACCF/AHA STEMI Guideline and 2014 AHA/ACC NSTE-ACS Guideline", "Landmark trials: ISCHEMIA, COMPLETE, CULPRIT-SHOCK, DanGer Shock, REDUCE-AMI"], "guidelines": [{"society": "ESC/ACC/AHA/WHF", "text": "Myocardial infarction requires detection of a rise and/or fall of cardiac troponin with at least one value above the 99th-percentile URL together with objective evidence of acute myocardial ischemia.", "year": "2018"}, {"society": "ESC", "text": "In patients presenting without persistent ST-elevation, use validated 0/1h (or 0/2h) high-sensitivity troponin algorithms with assay-specific cutoffs to accelerate rule-out and rule-in of MI.", "cor": "I", "loe": "B", "year": "2023"}, {"society": "ESC", "text": "An immediate invasive strategy (<2h) is indicated in NSTE-ACS with very-high-risk features (hemodynamic instability, refractory ischemia, life-threatening arrhythmia, mechanical complication, or acute heart failure attributable to ACS).", "cor": "I", "loe": "C", "year": "2023"}, {"society": "ESC", "text": "An early invasive strategy (<24h) should be considered in high-risk NSTE-ACS defined by a rise/fall of troponin consistent with MI, dynamic ST/T changes, or a high GRACE risk score.", "cor": "IIa", "loe": "A", "year": "2023"}, {"society": "ACC/AHA", "text": "In STEMI, primary PCI is the recommended reperfusion strategy when it can be delivered in a timely fashion (first-medical-contact-to-device <=90 minutes at a PCI-capable center, <=120 minutes if transfer is required).", "cor": "I", "loe": "A", "year": "2025"}, {"society": "ACC/AHA", "text": "In patients with ACS and multivessel disease undergoing PCI who are not in cardiogenic shock, complete revascularization of significant non-culprit lesions (at the index procedure or staged) is recommended to reduce recurrent events.", "cor": "I", "year": "2025"}, {"society": "ACC/AHA", "text": "A radial approach is preferred over a femoral approach for PCI in ACS to reduce bleeding, vascular complications, and mortality.", "cor": "I", "loe": "A", "year": "2025"}, {"society": "ACC/AHA", "text": "High-intensity statin therapy should be initiated in all patients with ACS regardless of baseline LDL cholesterol, with addition of ezetimibe and a PCSK9-directed agent as needed to reach guideline LDL-C goals.", "cor": "I", "year": "2025"}]};
